<h2><i class="fa fa-floppy-o"></i> Install</h2>
<p>You'll need a computer with at least 2GB RAM and 40GB available disk space. It should be running a fresh and updated version of Ubuntu Server 14.04 LTS.</p>
<p>Login and enter this command...
</p>
<pre class="top-gap">
curl engines.onl/install | bash
</pre>

<div class="btn-group">
  <button type="button" class="btn btn-default dropdown-toggle" data-toggle="dropdown" aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false">
    What will this command do? <span class="caret"></span>
  </button>
  <ul class="dropdown-menu dropdown_help">
    <li>Download and run scripts that:<br>
    1. Makes sure that Git is installed.<br>
    2. Download the Engines installer software (into a directory called EnginesInstaller).<br>
    3. Updates the base OS and installs Docker<br>
    4. Downloads the Engines system software (into /opt/engines, /var/lib/engines and /var/log/engines).<br>
    5. Downloads the required container images and starts Engines.</li>
  </ul>
</div>
<div class="btn-group">
  <button type="button" class="btn btn-default dropdown-toggle" data-toggle="dropdown" aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false">
    I'm an advanced user <span class="caret"></span>
  </button>
  <ul class="dropdown-menu dropdown_help">
    <li>If you don't like to curl | bash, you might prefer:<pre>sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install git
git clone https://github.com/EnginesOS/EnginesInstaller
cd EnginesInstaller
sudo ./install_engines.sh</pre>
<p>
While Ubuntu Server 14.04 LTS is recommended, Engines can run on Server and
Desktop versions of Ubuntu 14.04 and higher. Please note that if you run
Engines on a Desktop version of Ubuntu, you will need to disable dnsmasq.
</p>
<p>
Technical installation instructions, and a guide on how to install on
AWS: <%= link_to ("Engines installation " + content_tag(:i, nil, class: 'fa fa-github') +
 " GitHub page").html_safe, "https://github.com/EnginesOS/System/wiki/Installation",
 target: "_engines_github", class: 'btn btn-default' %>
</p>
</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<p class="top-gap">You may need to enter your computer's admin password to start the installation. You will be prompted to set a timezone. The installer will take about half an hour to run. The URL that you will use to access your Engines web interface will appear at the end of the process.</p>
<p>Open a web browser (on a device that is connected to the same local network as your new server). Enter the URL and sign in to Engines.</p>
<pre>Username 'admin', password 'password'</pre>
<p>Complete the setup wizard and you're ready to install applications.</p>

<h3><i class="fa fa-trash-o"></i> Uninstall</h3>
<p>Open a new terminal window and enter...</p>
<pre>sudo EnginesInstaller/obliterate_engines_no_warning.sh</pre>
<p>This command will uninstall the Engines system software, remove the Engines installer software and delete all Docker images and containers.</p>
<div class="btn-group">
  <button type="button" class="btn btn-default dropdown-toggle" data-toggle="dropdown" aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false">
    The uninstaller didn't work! <span class="caret"></span>
  </button>
  <ul class="dropdown-menu dropdown_help">
    <li>Make sure that you run the uninstall command from the same directory that you were in when you started the installation, which will be the parent of EnginesInstaller.</li>
    <li>If your terminal is in the EnginesInstaller directory, enter 'cd ..' and then run the uninstall command again.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

</div>
